1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:28,199
[SPEAKER_00] Thank you very much, Governor Vujicic, dear Boris. On behalf of all of us, thank you for a wonderful evening. It was such a fantastic mixture of history and culture. And thank you for working hard to secure good weather.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] Before I get into my speech, I want to recognize the work of the two teams, the IMF and the creation team, for organizing this conference. And I suggest we give these guys a round of applause. Thank you.

3
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] It is fantastic to be with you again. I am particularly pleased that this time, the Commission wisely allowed Valdis Dombrovskis to be here. Last time, he was sent as an ambassador to an inauguration, if I remember correctly. I can say that listening to you last evening,

4
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] gave me a very high degree of confidence that this time it will be different. This time Europe will stand up for itself, for its citizens, and for the betterment of the whole world.

5
00:01:39,000 --> 00:02:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] We are together at the time of higher uncertainty. The fog over our heads is actually thicker. And that makes it even more important to compare notes and see through this uncertainty and make the best out of the opportunities challenge always presents.

6
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] I want to start before I get into the challenges. I want to reflect on the successes this region has achieved. We have had three remarkable decades of reforms promoting economic openness and integration.

7
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] We have had three remarkable decades of reforms in the future. We have had three remarkable decades of the future.

8
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:32,000
[UNKNOWN] We have had three remarkable decades of the future. We have had three remarkable decades of the future.

9
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] We have had three remarkable decades of the future. We have had three remarkable decades of the future.

10
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] We have had three remarkable decades of the future. We have had three remarkable decades of the future.

11
00:02:34,000 --> 00:03:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] And then, for some, for some within the EU as member states, for others within the EU family as candidate countries. And we should not underestimate how significant that step towards enlarging the European family, these steps, one after another, have been.

12
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] As Boris reminded us, this has led to significant convergence of countries with their better-off peers. Since the mid-90s, incomes have more than doubled. And the gap relative to the advanced Europe has shrunk sharply.

13
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:41,080
[SPEAKER_00] Manufacturing became a catalyst for productivity growth as integration into European and global

14
00:03:41,080 --> 00:03:52,120
[SPEAKER_00] value chains helped the CEE economies reach beyond their domestic markets.

15
00:03:52,120 --> 00:03:59,060
[SPEAKER_00] And at the same time, openness to foreign direct investment accelerated capital accumulation

16
00:03:59,060 --> 00:04:01,479
[SPEAKER_00] and technology transfer.

17
00:04:01,479 --> 00:04:09,460
[SPEAKER_00] And of course, EU accession played and continues to play a huge role.

18
00:04:09,460 --> 00:04:16,139
[SPEAKER_00] Powered by domestic structural reforms put in place on the path to EU accession, countries

19
00:04:16,139 --> 00:04:23,399
[SPEAKER_00] that have joined the EU, accelerated their income convergence with advanced Europe, and

20
00:04:23,399 --> 00:04:28,120
[SPEAKER_00] outperformed comparable countries outside of the bloc.

21
00:04:28,120 --> 00:04:33,540
[SPEAKER_00] So, what is the conclusion so far?

22
00:04:33,540 --> 00:04:35,540
[SPEAKER_00] Well done.

23
00:04:35,540 --> 00:04:40,620
[SPEAKER_00] Second, well, we have also unfinished business.

24
00:04:40,620 --> 00:04:43,540
[SPEAKER_00] The journey is far, far from being completed.

25
00:04:43,540 --> 00:04:50,959
[SPEAKER_00] One thing that we have observed with a little bit of sadness is very often, if not always,

26
00:04:50,959 --> 00:04:57,959
[SPEAKER_00] when countries join the European Union, the drive for reform eases somewhat.

27
00:04:57,959 --> 00:05:04,379
[SPEAKER_00] I was just talking to our friend from Moldova, saying, look, why are you an accession country?

28
00:05:04,379 --> 00:05:05,379
[SPEAKER_00] Step on the pedal.

29
00:05:05,379 --> 00:05:10,379
[SPEAKER_00] Because once you get in, there would be this natural tendency to say, oh, thank God we are

30
00:05:10,379 --> 00:05:11,379
[SPEAKER_00] in.

31
00:05:11,379 --> 00:05:12,379
[SPEAKER_00] We can relax.

32
00:05:12,379 --> 00:05:13,800
[SPEAKER_00] We can relax.

33
00:05:13,800 --> 00:05:14,800
[SPEAKER_00] But relax we cannot.

34
00:05:14,800 --> 00:05:24,879
[SPEAKER_00] We have to recognize that after the global financial crisis, we have seen a drop in investment, and

35
00:05:24,879 --> 00:05:31,800
[SPEAKER_00] this has contributed to a productivity slump that has only worsened after COVID.

36
00:05:31,800 --> 00:05:37,220
[SPEAKER_00] Revitalizing reforms is absolutely paramount.

37
00:05:37,220 --> 00:05:49,220
[SPEAKER_00] We see how we are being affected by tightness of our labor markets, by high energy costs, by the

38
00:05:49,220 --> 00:05:59,060
[SPEAKER_00] fact that technology is moving very fast, and if we are not moving even faster, we risk to

39
00:05:59,060 --> 00:06:00,060
[SPEAKER_00] to fall behind.

40
00:06:00,060 --> 00:06:13,360
[SPEAKER_00] So we -- I would really urge us to be ambitious to pursue reforms, and to do it because, on top

41
00:06:13,360 --> 00:06:19,759
[SPEAKER_00] of everything, we are now faced with huge new challenges.

42
00:06:19,759 --> 00:06:29,040
[SPEAKER_00] The sweeping disruptions to the world trade system are plain for everybody to

43
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:34,360
[SPEAKER_00] to see, the way we function is being tested.

44
00:06:34,360 --> 00:06:45,160
[SPEAKER_00] And while most of the countries in this room are less impacted directly by U.S. tariffs,

45
00:06:45,160 --> 00:06:53,100
[SPEAKER_00] let us be very clear, the indirect impact is significant as these disruptions pose a major

46
00:06:53,100 --> 00:06:58,420
[SPEAKER_00] threat to the region's main trading partners.

47
00:06:58,420 --> 00:07:05,720
[SPEAKER_00] And to the overall economic model that Boris described so well, small, open economies need

48
00:07:05,720 --> 00:07:11,279
[SPEAKER_00] trade to improve the well-being of their people.

49
00:07:11,279 --> 00:07:18,100
[SPEAKER_00] Trade tensions and uncertainty complicate domestic and foreign investment plans, and this is particularly

50
00:07:18,100 --> 00:07:26,420
[SPEAKER_00] very painful for a region that needs access to modern production processes, needs more jobs

51
00:07:26,420 --> 00:07:35,420
[SPEAKER_00] in high productivity sectors, and needs this open world to expand economic opportunities.

52
00:07:35,420 --> 00:07:40,740
[SPEAKER_00] So what is my main message?

53
00:07:40,740 --> 00:07:49,800
[SPEAKER_00] Standing still, taking shelter when the winds are blowing, hoping for the storm to pass is

54
00:07:49,800 --> 00:07:51,740
[SPEAKER_00] not a plan.

55
00:07:51,740 --> 00:08:00,120
[SPEAKER_00] Standing still, it would be much wiser to assume that many of the shifts we are witnessing

56
00:08:00,120 --> 00:08:05,060
[SPEAKER_00] are here to state, that more storms are going to hit us.

57
00:08:05,060 --> 00:08:07,060
[SPEAKER_00] So what do we do?

58
00:08:07,060 --> 00:08:20,740
[SPEAKER_00] In a stormy weather, how can we actually turn the winds from a risk for our navigation to a

59
00:08:20,740 --> 00:08:31,540
[SPEAKER_00] to a tailwind from, you call it the Adriatic border, make the Adriatic border work for us, for

60
00:08:31,540 --> 00:08:34,139
[SPEAKER_00] our sail, not against it.

61
00:08:34,139 --> 00:08:39,539
[SPEAKER_00] I want to point to three critical priorities.

62
00:08:39,539 --> 00:08:49,740
[SPEAKER_00] First, steering a steady course in terms of macroeconomic policy, monetary and fiscal stability

63
00:08:49,740 --> 00:08:56,539
[SPEAKER_00] as our most reliable means to deal with uncertainty.

64
00:08:56,539 --> 00:09:07,419
[SPEAKER_00] Second, getting our ship in better order so it can move faster, and that means pursue structural

65
00:09:07,419 --> 00:09:08,539
[SPEAKER_00] reforms for growth.

66
00:09:08,539 --> 00:09:16,539
[SPEAKER_00] Third, integrate more deeply into and within the single market of the EU.

67
00:09:16,539 --> 00:09:21,340
[SPEAKER_00] Strength through regional cooperation.

68
00:09:21,340 --> 00:09:25,340
[SPEAKER_00] Let me briefly discuss each one of these points.

69
00:09:25,340 --> 00:09:32,139
[SPEAKER_00] priority one, actions to mitigate uncertainty.

70
00:09:32,139 --> 00:09:38,139
[SPEAKER_00] It is always important to have sound monetary policy, sound fiscal policy.

71
00:09:38,139 --> 00:09:44,139
[SPEAKER_00] Even more important when uncertainty is higher.

72
00:09:44,139 --> 00:09:50,940
[SPEAKER_00] I think economic and financial stability is the anchor on which you can build your plans.

73
00:09:50,940 --> 00:09:54,940
[SPEAKER_00] I see some emerging risks there.

74
00:09:54,940 --> 00:10:01,740
[SPEAKER_00] on the monetary policy side.

75
00:10:01,740 --> 00:10:05,740
[SPEAKER_00] The pressure on central bank independence has become harder.

76
00:10:05,740 --> 00:10:09,740
[SPEAKER_00] We all have a role to play to protect it.

77
00:10:09,740 --> 00:10:18,539
[SPEAKER_00] I know that in the round table we had yesterday, this was a topic that came time and again.

78
00:10:18,539 --> 00:10:25,340
[SPEAKER_00] We also recognize that on the fiscal front, how many of you are finance ministers and

79
00:10:25,340 --> 00:10:29,340
[SPEAKER_00] those working in finance authorities?

80
00:10:29,340 --> 00:10:31,340
[SPEAKER_00] Raise your hand.

81
00:10:31,340 --> 00:10:33,340
[SPEAKER_00] Let me see.

82
00:10:33,340 --> 00:10:42,139
[SPEAKER_00] How many are central bankers?

83
00:10:42,139 --> 00:10:44,139
[SPEAKER_00] Very good central bankers this time.

84
00:10:44,139 --> 00:10:46,139
[SPEAKER_00] I have an upper hand in this audience.

85
00:10:46,139 --> 00:10:54,139
[SPEAKER_00] For the finance authorities, I am very keen to see central bankers staying united and making

86
00:10:54,139 --> 00:10:58,940
[SPEAKER_00] a strong case for central bank independence for the fiscal authorities.

87
00:10:58,940 --> 00:11:02,940
[SPEAKER_00] It is going to be a very tough time ahead of you.

88
00:11:02,940 --> 00:11:03,740
[SPEAKER_00] Why?

89
00:11:03,740 --> 00:11:13,019
[SPEAKER_00] Because over the last couple of years, what has happened is shock after shock after shock

90
00:11:13,019 --> 00:11:16,779
[SPEAKER_00] forced more fiscal largeness.

91
00:11:16,779 --> 00:11:22,299
[SPEAKER_00] They forced providing more support to household and to businesses.

92
00:11:22,860 --> 00:11:29,659
